{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/glandular-fever-infectious-mononucleosis/background-information/prognosis/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"e1e96b16-d495-5d31-a3dd-0b7f997675c9","slug":"prognosis","fullItemName":"Prognosis","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 7ff4a3ad-6ef1-44db-b3d7-9bb415d919e0 --><h2>What is the prognosis?</h2><!-- end field 7ff4a3ad-6ef1-44db-b3d7-9bb415d919e0 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 83a98621-674d-4cd0-aa5d-fea784eb4d71 --><!-- begin field dd4575cc-a11b-4d32-9f60-a059a5753e17 --><ul><li><strong>In most people, glandular fever is self limiting and lasts 2–4 weeks </strong>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/glandular-fever-infectious-mononucleosis/references/\">CDC, 2018</a>]<strong>. </strong>Occasionally the disease course can be prolonged (lasting for weeks or months) [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/glandular-fever-infectious-mononucleosis/references/\">Rezk, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/glandular-fever-infectious-mononucleosis/references/\">De Paor, 2016</a>]. <ul><li>Serious <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/glandular-fever-infectious-mononucleosis/background-information/complications/\">complications</a> are rare and include upper airways obstruction, splenic rupture, and neutropenia. In immunocompromized people, EBV infection may result in malignant disease, such as Hodgkin's lymphoma and nasopharyngeal carcinoma.</li><li>Fatigue is common and usually lasts for a few weeks, or for several months in a minority of people (about 10%). </li></ul></li><li><strong>Epstein-Barr virus (EBV) infection leads to a lifelong latent carrier state (the virus remains in the body lifelong). </strong>The virus may reactivate but does not always cause symptoms. People who are immunocompromized are more likely to develop symptoms if EBV reactivates [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/glandular-fever-infectious-mononucleosis/references/\">CDC, 2018</a>].</li></ul><!-- end field dd4575cc-a11b-4d32-9f60-a059a5753e17 --><!-- end item 83a98621-674d-4cd0-aa5d-fea784eb4d71 -->","topic":{"id":"79787412-82dc-54ee-8f4d-82bb69926abd","topicId":"c9504b30-5339-4b0e-ae98-8637960b13dd","topicName":"Glandular fever (infectious mononucleosis)","slug":"glandular-fever-infectious-mononucleosis","lastRevised":"Last revised in March 2020","chapters":[{"id":"fe86b21c-212e-588d-8fa4-c3ba5660eac1","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"5f9a86f5-ef8f-544d-913a-a590a53535c1","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"0a089fd0-524b-5897-8e6a-ddf549b68ab1","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"4bb31918-f826-5ad9-94c9-277390a6c0a6","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"1b1796e9-9f11-5086-8044-c244b38cab9f","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"e8f82c54-74bc-5c96-8ae4-915ef47cdc57","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","subChapters":[{"id":"e297f8dd-9da6-5f6e-994d-22be9b9c25ce","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"3046ea37-29e3-531b-988d-b845fd950135","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Outcome measures"},{"id":"4e842d69-8714-5155-a670-debee1452013","slug":"audit-criteria","fullItemName":"Audit criteria"},{"id":"6002b762-9bc1-544a-8bd4-9a17721ee873","slug":"qof-indicators","fullItemName":"QOF indicators"},{"id":"91fe23ad-4802-56ea-b009-10c57fe2af06","slug":"qipp-options-for-local-implementation","fullItemName":"QIPP - Options for local implementation"},{"id":"ff9cc4d0-961b-5fb9-9e50-cd71cb09ddb1","slug":"nice-quality-standards","fullItemName":"NICE quality standards"}]},{"id":"41104316-b37f-5c24-a33f-610e21b30c2d","ful